@Ivanskiin12 Dude, my whole point is that I (and obviously you, given you haven't answered to any question about actual knowledge in this thread) am not an ignorant for not knowing things about something that is not even widely popular in the foreign country it happens to be in. It's no surprise that you didn't even nearly get what I mean by privilege, but I'll try and clarify. I'm from Argentina and my family would be considered middle class. I have never in my life been able to fly on an airplane, I've just been to places close by like Chile and the south of Brazil. I don't live a luxurious life, I'm now working and making what would be 200$ per month and my parents together might make something like 2500$ per month. I don't know what you might think of those amounts, but I can tell you that the 60% of my country's (poor)population would only dream of making them. The other day, my girlfriend was robbed in her house and the police here is a joke. Some years ago, the police stopped working because of some problem with their salary, and we had to go out to the street to protect our property. Oh and btw, our inflation rate is ~50% per year.

You on the other hand, live in a beautiful city rated in the top liveable ones, in a pretty economically stable country and are able to walk in the street with your phone without minding what's the closes place you can throw it if someone tries to rob you. Your house probably doesn't have a huge metal fence in the front like ours do. All of this combined with the facts that your education system is great, a person alone makes far more than both my parents per month, you speak english natively, you have an Australian passport, and you can afford to travel; puts you in a VERY privileged position, one in which you have the resources, free time and stress free situation to, just in case you want to, dedicate time to make yourself more knowledgeable about everything you want.

I didn't mean to compete with you if that's what you thought. Just thought that you shouldn't be calling people ignorant for not knowing stuff about your country, as well as you are not an ignorant for CLEARLY not knowing anything about Polo teams in Argentina.

@jameskappos6678 I agree with you about the beaches James. I'm not a beach person anyway but Melbourne has beaches literally 2-3km from the CBD (Port Melbourne? Albert Park?). Yes they aren't SURF beaches, but not being a surf beach doesn't mean it's not a "real" beach. There is a lot you can enjoy at a beach besides surfing, and surf culture can actually ruin a beach suburb. The inner-Melbourne suburbs with beaches don't revolve around their beach so have much more to offer, and just happen to have a beach as a bonus, mostly west facing so they get incredible sunsets over the bay. 

They are just different. If you're into surf culture, big waves and beach tourism then I agree, Sydney absolutely wins for quantity and quality with an abundance of them from the northern beaches down to the Shire. But for those who prefer quiet beaches with no surf culture in the middle of artsy inner-city neighbourhoods, to walk the dog and take in beautiful sunsets reflecting off the bay, it has to be Melbourne. Different strokes for different folks. 

And for those who are into surfing, Australia's best surf beaches are in Victoria & WA anyway, not NSW...

