@mjcats2011 - As you know, there is a A$1.7 billion upgrade to Myki to make it an 'open loop' payment/ticketing system to allow mobile device, credit/debit card and Myki branded card transactions with a planned roll out from 2024 for all PTV metro train, Yarra tram, V/line regional coach/train, local bus and ferry services across the state. The recently introduced $10.00 daily fare for all public transport services across the state is the prelude to the new Myki 'tap & travel' payment/ticketing system.

By the way, having traveled in Sydney,  I don't think Sydney metro public transport services are any better than Melbourne.  

As in any public transport planning and operation, each state develops their own intra-state public transport network/s to suit local state needs, so you can not really compare which state has a better PT network/s.

@chrismckellar9350  What I mean is regards to Myki instead of leveraging on existing systems like Opal did, they tried to invent from scratch and ended up with a substandard system.

How comes NSW and WA with their excellent MetroNet project can manage a number of projects at a time, and we in Victoria we struggle to manage one (level crossing removals aside). When other jurisdictions recruit from overseas, it's Howard Collins or Andy Lord or Andy Byford. Who do we get? Jim Betts. About as useful to the cause as a chocolate teapot.

Victoria never learns. When it comes to PT planning and implementation, we suck.

@mjcats2011 - MyKi was purposely built  for Victoria developed by the Victorian State Government to replace then Metcard in 2012 as an improved integrated 'tap & travel' payment/ticketing system for Victoria's regional commuter trains, local buses, Yarra trams and Melbourne Metro trains. The current upgrade of Myki is being developed by Conduent with planned rollout from 2024 with a completion date of 2025.

Opal card was built for TfNSW by Cubic initially as an 'open loop' system but introduced in 2012 as a 'closed' collective system. In 2017, the Opal software was upgraded for OpalPay being an 'open loop' system system for smart/mobile devices, credit/debit card and Opal brand child, senior and other concession fares.

With regards to your other  comments, each state has their ways of doing things, so trying to compare who is better is a bit ridiculous. At least with Victoria, they think state wide compared to other states.

@mjcats2011I've checked the timetable and the fastest all stations journey time is 50 minutes. It used to be faster before the timetable was slowed down in 2005 to improve on-time running statistics.   It should also be pointed out that there are 18 intermediate stations between Central and Hornsby.  

Surprisingly, the journey time between Central and Hornsby via the Northern Line over a longer distance of 34km, with 16 intermediate stations, is actually a minute faster at 49 minutes outbound, no doubt in part due to express running between Redfern and Burwood, but slower at 54 minutes inbound.   The Northern Intercity express service, stopping only at Strathfield and Epping,  takes 38 minutes. 

These journey times will be significantly improved with the proposed digital signaling and ATO upgrades.

@daveg2104 Thing is, if there were more than 4 stops left as diesel trains, I'd be less confused. It's the fact they get so close to the end of the existing line and _then_ stop that confuses me!

But also yes, I wonder how much more it'd cost to also extend the line into Nowra proper. I mean, in comparison to the road projects for getting down to the south coast like the Berry Bypass. 

Though I don't know what the bus services are like from Bomaderry to the rest of the South Coast (the few times I've taken the train down there's been family with a car at the other end to pick up and go the rest of the way). Would extending the train line into Nowra provide any benefits over a bus route I wonder? Would people travel to or from Nowra more if the T4 was finished, fully electrified down to Nowra? And, I know the locals would hate this, but I wonder what the usage would be if it were extended down to Jervis Bay itself? Make it a lot easier for  Sydneysiders (and others along the train line) to get to that holiday area

@scagren We can agree to disagree there. 

If your daily commute was 20ks each way and you pay a max of 10AUD for the whole trip, I'd argue that's an absolute bargain. Nevermind that said fare also allows any spontaneous travel you may wish to do that day beyond your daily commute - e.g. having dinner in St Kilda.

Using London for comparison as it's the system I'm most familiar with, a trip from Harrow to Aldgate on the tube (20ks as the crow flies) would cost a bit under 10AUD *one way*, nevermind that in London the fares are charged per trip, so you couldn't make any spontaneous journeys throughout the day.

@jdillon8360 the reason is more historical than anything. Its just always been that way since the beginning. 

The reason the City Circle does not reverse anymore was because going anti-clockwise around that tunnel forces everything across a single flat junction at Jolimont in both directions which created a lot of conflict and severely limited capacity on the Clifton Hill group.

In terms of the Caulfield loop, there are two reason why this loop now always runs anticlockwise. The first is because the Selective Door Opening Beacons have only been installed in one direction. An HCMT running the reverse direction cannot release its doors at any loop station. The second reason (and in my own opinion the most useful) is that it allows a direct connection from the Loop into Southern Cross and Flinders Street stations. Until the Caulfield Loop was fixed in one direction, you could not get to those two stations from the loop in the PM Peak without first leaving the loop to North Melbourne, Richmond or Jolimont and then changing trains. This was especially a problem for anyone trying to connect to a regional train at Southern Cross, especially now that VLines ridership is quite high now. This also put enormous pressure on the Trams heading towards Spencer St for the same reason.
